{"action": "edit", "code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    In the input, you should see some shapes, all of which have a main color with one or two grey connected pixels.                                                     \n    The output grid size changes in length by removed any black columns that separate the shapes.                                                                       \n    To make the output, you have to make any grey pixels the same color as the pixels to which it is connected.                                                         \n    Remove columns of black pixels.                                                                                                                                     \n    Align the middle and right shapes so that the former grey squares are connected.                                                                                    \n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    output_grid = make_grey_connected_pixels_same_color(output_grid)\n    output_grid = remove_black_columns(output_grid)\n    output_grid = align_grey_squares(input_grid, output_grid)\n    return output_grid\ndef _hole5(grid: np.ndarray, square: Tuple[int, int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and a square, this function colors the square red if it is surrounded by grey pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    i, j = square\n    size = 1\n    while i - size >= 0 and j - size >= 0 and (i + size < grid.shape[0]) and (j + size < grid.shape[1]):\n        if np.all(grid[i - size:i + size + 1, j - size:j + size + 1] == grey):\n            grid[i - size:i + size + 1, j - size:j + size + 1] = red\n            size += 1\n        else:\n            break\n    return grid\ndef make_grey_connected_pixels_same_color(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an input grid and makes any grey pixels the same color as the pixels to which it is connected.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    for i in range(output_grid.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(output_grid.shape[1]):\n            if output_grid[i][j] == grey:\n                neighbors = []\n                if i > 0:\n                    neighbors.append(output_grid[i - 1][j])\n                if i < output_grid.shape[0] - 1:\n                    neighbors.append(output_grid[i + 1][j])\n                if j > 0:\n                    neighbors.append(output_grid[i][j - 1])\n                if j < output_grid.shape[1] - 1:\n                    neighbors.append(output_grid[i][j + 1])\n                for neighbor in neighbors:\n                    if neighbor != grey:\n                        output_grid[i][j] = neighbor\n                        break\n    return output_grid\ndef remove_black_columns(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an input grid and removes any black columns that separate the shapes.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    black_columns = []\n    for j in range(output_grid.shape[1]):\n        if np.all(output_grid[:, j] == black):\n            black_columns.append(j)\n    output_grid = np.delete(output_grid, black_columns, axis=1)\n    return output_grid\ndef align_grey_squares(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    In the input, you should see some shapes, all of which have a main color with one or two grey connected pixels.\n    The output grid size changes in length by removed any black columns that separate the shapes.\n    To make the output, you have to make any grey pixels the same color as the pixels to which it is connected.\n    Remove columns of black pixels.\n    Align the middle and right shapes so that the former grey squares are connected.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    output_grid = mak